{"type":"message","id":"d9fb6f60","parentId":"00eb850c","timestamp":"2026-04-16T08:26:37.915Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_VjAAmqgZzgDdzHHRA69QpkWh|fc_0156872873475ee30169e09d3d99c88191a82a2f79fc05978f","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/home/node/.openclaw/workspace/vault/Clean/projects/aurelius/master_context.md","content":"# Aurelius Master Context\n\n## Project summary\nAurelius is a research-heavy project centered on a systems-level protocol framework. The corpus contains protocol architecture, mechanistic analyses, intervention modules, diagnostics, photobiomodulation material, and related supporting documents.\n\n## Corpus characteristics\n- Large compared with Apollo, with many near-duplicate exports and filename variants\n- Multiple canonical long-form research documents already identified\n- Some conversation-derived context exists in the recovered Gemini-derived timeline\n- Some artifacts were previously misbucketed into `other` because classification was intentionally conservative\n\n## Current objective\nCreate a canonical, retrieval-friendly Aurelius knowledge pack that preserves the strongest source documents while reducing duplicate noise and keeping provenance visible.\n\n## Working structure\n- Canonical research documents live under `vault/Clean/projects/aurelius/sources/`\n- Project operational docs summarize state, decisions, tasks, and deliverables\n- Shared conversation sources should remain distinct from project summaries\n\n## Retrieval strategy\n- Use compact project docs for synthesis and orientation\n- Use canonical sources for evidence and detailed retrieval\n- Avoid indexing duplicate filename variants when an equivalent canonical file already exists\n\n## Immediate next stage\n- Keep only canonical Aurelius documents in the primary ingestion path\n- Use operational docs to stabilize recall across the large source set\n- Later, consider thematic splitting by subdomain such as diagnostics, endocrine models, peptides, and photobiomodulation\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/home/node/.openclaw/workspace/vault/Clean/projects/aurelius/master_context.md\",\"content\":\"# Aurelius Master Context\\n\\n## Project summary\\nAurelius is a research-heavy project centered on a systems-level protocol framework. The corpus contains protocol architecture, mechanistic analyses, intervention modules, diagnostics, photobiomodulation material, and related supporting documents.\\n\\n## Corpus characteristics\\n- Large compared with Apollo, with many near-duplicate exports and filename variants\\n- Multiple canonical long-form research documents already identified\\n- Some conversation-derived context exists in the recovered Gemini-derived timeline\\n- Some artifacts were previously misbucketed into `other` because classification was intentionally conservative\\n\\n## Current objective\\nCreate a canonical, retrieval-friendly Aurelius knowledge pack that preserves the strongest source documents while reducing duplicate noise and keeping provenance visible.\\n\\n## Working structure\\n- Canonical research documents live under `vault/Clean/projects/aurelius/sources/`\\n- Project operational docs summarize state, decisions, tasks, and deliverables\\n- Shared conversation sources should remain distinct from project summaries\\n\\n## Retrieval strategy\\n- Use compact project docs for synthesis and orientation\\n- Use canonical sources for evidence and detailed retrieval\\n- Avoid indexing duplicate filename variants when an equivalent canonical file already exists\\n\\n## Immediate next stage\\n- Keep only canonical Aurelius documents in the primary ingestion path\\n- Use operational docs to stabilize recall across the large source set\\n- Later, consider thematic splitting by subdomain such as diagnostics, endocrine models, peptides, and photobiomodulation\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_w4zFDS8ZqHeLpFpY1l01xDJV|fc_0156872873475ee30169e09d3d99d88191959769a3ab01f414","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/home/node/.openclaw/workspace/vault/Clean/projects/aurelius/decisions.md","content":"# Aurelius Decisions\n\n## Confirmed decisions\n- Use canonical Aurelius files as the primary ingestion evidence set\n- Suppress duplicate and truncated filename variants where a full canonical source exists\n- Preserve provenance by keeping source files in the project tree rather than collapsing everything into one synthetic note\n- Use operational summary docs to improve retrieval and project continuity\n\n## Working assumptions\n- Aurelius is a distinct project family and should remain separated from Apollo in both summaries and source layout\n- Shared Gemini-export material should not be treated as an Aurelius-only source unless explicitly sliced\n- The cleaned corpus, not the raw vault, should be the default LightRAG ingestion surface\n\n## Open decisions\n- Whether the Aurelius corpus should be split into thematic subfolders before ingestion\n- Whether the XLSX material should be converted into markdown or summarized separately\n- Whether to produce a distilled protocol summary that sits above the current source set\n\n## Recommendation\nProceed with the current canonical source set plus compact operational docs first. After retrieval is tested, decide whether thematic sub-indexing is worth the extra complexity.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/home/node/.openclaw/workspace/vault/Clean/projects/aurelius/decisions.md\",\"content\":\"# Aurelius Decisions\\n\\n## Confirmed decisions\\n- Use canonical Aurelius files as the primary ingestion evidence set\\n- Suppress duplicate and truncated filename variants where a full canonical source exists\\n- Preserve provenance by keeping source files in the project tree rather than collapsing everything into one synthetic note\\n- Use operational summary docs to improve retrieval and project continuity\\n\\n## Working assumptions\\n- Aurelius is a distinct project family and should remain separated from Apollo in both summaries and source layout\\n- Shared Gemini-export material should not be treated as an Aurelius-only source unless explicitly sliced\\n- The cleaned corpus, not the raw vault, should be the default LightRAG ingestion surface\\n\\n## Open decisions\\n- Whether the Aurelius corpus should be split into thematic subfolders before ingestion\\n- Whether the XLSX material should be converted into markdown or summarized separately\\n- Whether to produce a distilled protocol summary that sits above the current source set\\n\\n## Recommendation\\nProceed with the current canonical source set plus compact operational docs first. After retrieval is tested, decide whether thematic sub-indexing is worth the extra complexity.\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_PnMES0mcukjyRIlO04ur2jR9|fc_0156872873475ee30169e09d3d99e4819196658dcdd10f6b9c","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/home/node/.openclaw/workspace/vault/Clean/projects/aurelius/tasks.md","content":"# Aurelius Tasks\n\n## Now\n- Preserve the canonical Aurelius corpus for ingestion\n- Build a clean ingestion pack that excludes suppressed duplicates\n- Keep project summary docs concise and retrieval-friendly\n\n## Next\n- Test retrieval quality using summary docs plus canonical sources\n- Decide whether to convert or summarize spreadsheet content\n- Identify any remaining misclassified Aurelius artifacts in `other`\n\n## Later\n- Create thematic subpacks such as diagnostics, protocol architecture, peptides, and photobiomodulation\n- Extract project decisions and protocol milestones from conversation history\n- Produce higher-level protocol summaries for rapid orientation\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/home/node/.openclaw/workspace/vault/Clean/projects/aurelius/tasks.md\",\"content\":\"# Aurelius Tasks\\n\\n## Now\\n- Preserve the canonical Aurelius corpus for ingestion\\n- Build a clean ingestion pack that excludes suppressed duplicates\\n- Keep project summary docs concise and retrieval-friendly\\n\\n## Next\\n-